Paying unexpected calls on Wal-Mart stores is one way Chairman Sam Walton has kept 
in touch with everyday happenings.  Other Wal-Mart executives follow his example.  
Walton's personality permeates operations and his whole family is in the business.  
People say Sam is as old-fashioned and homespun as his principles, which declare the 
customer is always right.  He is happy to chat with customers, but shuns the press 
especially when asked about his massive fortune.  Walton turns 71 in March.  He was 
born in Oklahoma, the son of a mortgage banker.  He opened Wal-Mart Discount City in 
1962.  The rest is history.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d066"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890615-0263"
SELECTOR="J"
SUMMARIZER="I">

Wal-Mart founder Sam Walton helped the check-out clerks in his Fort Walton Beach, 
Florida store on Tuesday evening.  He was visiting when a computer problem shut down 
the cash registers, so he took a note pad and started writing down prices for customers so 
their bills could be added more quickly.  Many recognized him and he shook hands and 
chatted.  Walton, 71, is known for his down-home style and surprise visits.  He had come 
to the Fort Walton Beach store to attend a promotional concert in its parking lot.  Walton 
stayed for the concert and led the Wal-Mart cheer.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d066"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890711-0223"
