SUMMARIZER="I">

Wal-Mart Stores Inc.'s Visitors Center opens Wednesday, 40 years after Sam Walton 
opened a business in the same building in Bentonville, Arkansas.  The center chronicles 
the rise of the nation's fastest-growing discount chain.  After working for the J.C. Penney 
Co. and a tour in the army, Walton opened a Ben Franklin Store in nearby Newport.  He 
moved to Bentonville in 1950.  He opened more Ben Franklin Stores, but the company 
did not like his plan for discount stores in rural areas.  Walton and his brother opened the 
first Wal-Mart Discount City in 1962.  By  early 1990 Wal-Mart owned 1,402 stores and 
employed 272,000.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d066"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT922-14265"
SELECTOR="J"
SUMMARIZER="I">

Sam Walton is arguably the most important retailer of his generation.  The owner of a 
general store in the backwaters of Arkansas in 1950 became the world's largest retailer, 
with annual sales of almost $44 billion.  Success can be attributed to Walton's personality 
and his willingness to challenge retailing orthodoxy.  He was a frugal, modest, hard-
working man, who made pop-in visits and delivered pep talks.  Employee satisfaction 
was a vital ingredient, with bonus payments and profit-sharing plans.  Also essential is 
Wal-Mart's year around high-volume, cut-price selling.  Walton proved discount stores 
could be successful in rural towns and drove out hundreds of small main-street stores.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d066"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT923-5068"
SELECTOR="J"
SUMMARIZER="I">

"Made in America: My Story" is Sam Walton autobiography and tells how he negotiated 
the pitfalls of being America's richest entrepreneur and a folk hero.  Walton, who died of 
cancer in April, was a dull, happily married, folksy, quail hunter.  Some question 
Walton's anti-union policies, the impact of Wal-Mart on Mom and Pop stores, and 
exploits of his children, but his book is all about "good ole" common sense and 
anecdotes.  He presents himself as an energetic, competitive, engaging, if one-
dimensional, character.  Publishers paid $4 million for him to have his final say.  Some 
may find it dreary and downbeat.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d066"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT944-12170"
SELECTOR="J"
SUMMARIZER="I">

Some may say "Wal-Mart: A History of Sam Walton's Retail Phenomenon" by Sandra 
Vance and Roy Scott profiles the American Dream.  Walton became one of the world's 
most successful businessmen, leaving the second-largest fortune in the world.  Most 
phenomenal was the rapid growth of the company, going from 38 stores to the largest in 
America in 20 years.  This scholarly work identifies Wal-Mart's ability to copy and 
adapt, staying open to new technology, and building the most efficient retail distribution 
system.  It highlights the streamlined, rapidly responding, management and includes the 
debate on whether Wal-Mart's impact on small towns was positive or negative.</SUM>
